article.headline: Tulsa 79, Jackson State 54
article.story: TULSA, Okla. (AP) Rod Earls scored 18 points for Tulsa and the Golden Hurricane held Jackson State to 34 percent shooting in a 79-54 victory on Monday. Tulsa is 6-1 for the first time since the 2002-03 season, which was also the last season in which it reached the NCAA Tournament. Tulsa hasn't achieved its sixth win before Jan. 14 during any of the past three seasons. Charles Ramsdell scored 13 points, all in the second half, and Ray Reese added 11 for Tulsa, which had 12 players score. The Hurricane outrebounded the smaller Tigers 47-31, led by eight by Calvin Walls and seven by Jamel McLean, and also blocked seven shots. Jackson State (4-6), which has yet to play a home game this year, was led by 31 points by Trey Johnson, who entered the game as NCAA Division I basketball's leading scorer at 29.8 points per game. Johnson made 10 of 22 field goals, including 5 of 9 3-point attempts, but his teammates combined to make just 10 field goals, including 1 of 10 3-point attempts. Julius Young had five of those 10 baskets and finished with 13 points. Earls, a 6-foot-2 junior guard, scored 15 points in the first half as Tulsa raced to a 36-17 halftime lead. He had three treys in the first half and finished 4 of 6 from 3-point range. Johnson had just nine points at the break on 3-of-10 shooting, but warmed up in the second half. Reese, a sophomore guard who has seen limited playing time thanks to the emergence of freshman starter Ben Uzoh, made the most of his 12 minutes. He hit a fallaway jumper at the buzzer to end the first half, then added three 3-pointers in the second half for his first double-figure scoring game of the season.
